-- Japan, China, India, Philippines, Thailand: Asian Bonds, Currency Preview
-- V. Ramakrishnan
-- 2010-07-14T23:06:17Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-14/japan-china-india-philippines-thailand-asian-bonds-currency-preview.html

          
          
             The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  
 Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary  Yoshito Sengoku  will hold a
media briefing at 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  
 The Bank of Japan will conclude a two-day policy board
meeting that began yesterday. BOJ Governor  Masaaki Shirakawa 
will hold a press briefing at 3:30 p.m. local time.  
 The Ministry of Finance will release at 8:50 a.m. its
figures on Japanese and foreign investment flows for domestic
and overseas securities during the week ended July 9. The
Ministry will announce at 10:30 a.m. the amount of 20-year bonds
it plans to sell on July 22.  
 The yield on the new 1.1 percent government bond due June
2020 was at 1.135 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co.,
the nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  
 The yen traded at 88.31 per dollar at 8:02 a.m. in Tokyo.  
 China: Economic growth slowed to 10.5 percent in the second
quarter from 11.9 percent in the prior three months, according
to the median estimate of economists surveyed by Bloomberg
before the data is released today. Consumer prices climbed 3.3
percent in June from a year earlier, the most since October 2008,
a separate survey showed before data also due today.  
 The yield on the 2.53 percent note due in June 2015 was
2.53 percent. The yuan was at 6.7745 per dollar.  
 India: The government will report primary articles
inflation, which includes changes in food prices, for the week
ended July 3. An index measuring wholesale costs of farm
products including lentils, rice and vegetables, a component of
the primary articles gauge, rose 16.08 percent in the previous
week from a year earlier.  
 The yield on the 7.80 percent bond due May 2020 was 7.63
percent. The rupee was at 46.6962.  
 Taiwan: The government will sell NT$40 billion ($1.25
billion) of five-year bonds today.  
 The yield on the 1.44 percent bond maturing March 2020 was
1.44 percent, according to Gretai Securities Market. The Taiwan
dollar traded at NT$32.19.  
 Thailand: The central bank will sell 60 billion baht ($1.86
billion) of 14-day bills today.  
 The yield on the 3.625 percent debt due in May 2015 was
3.46 percent. The baht was at 32.32.  
 Malaysia: The government will sell 80 million ringgit ($25
million) of 91-day bills and 100 million ringgit of 364-day
Islamic bills today.  
 The yield on the 3.835 percent debt maturing in August 2015
was 3.36 percent, according to Bursa Malaysia. The ringgit was
at 3.1978.  
 Philippines: The central bank will keep its benchmark
interest rate at a record-low 4 percent for a ninth meeting,
according to 13 of 14 economists surveyed by Bloomberg. One
predicted a quarter of a percentage point increase. The decision
is due at about 4 p.m. in Manila today.  
 The yield on the 7.75 percent debt due February 2020 was
7.40 percent, according to Tradition Financial Services. The
peso was at 46.26.  
